                <head>350. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> visited Turkey
                    December 6–7, during his 11-nation good will tour (December 3–23). The President
                    and his party arrived at Ankara from Italy at 3 p.m. on December 6. After an
                    airport greeting from President <persName corresp="#p_BC1">Bayar</persName> and
                    ceremonial functions, including a wreath-laying at the tomb of Ataturk, the
                    President met with <persName corresp="#p_BC1">Bayar</persName>, Prime Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_MA1">Menderes</persName>, and Foreign Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_ZFR1">Zorlu</persName> at the Presidential Palace.
                    (See <ref target="#d351">Document 351</ref>) After this meeting, the President
                    attended a formal dinner given by <persName corresp="#p_BC1">Bayar</persName> at
                    8:30 p.m. He returned to his residence at 11 p.m. At 7:30 a.m. on December 7,
                    the President, accompanied by President <persName corresp="#p_BC1"
                        >Bayar</persName>, left by helicopter for Esenboga Airport. He left Ankara
                    for Karachi at 8:10 a.m., following brief airport ceremonies. For text of the
                    joint communiqué issued after <persName>Eisenhower</persName>’s talks with
                    Turkish leaders, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>,
                    December 28, 1959, pages 932–933. <persName>Eisenhower</persName>’s
                    recollections of the meeting are in <hi rend="italic">Waging Peace</hi>, pages
                    492–493.</p>
            </div>
